---------------------------------------------------------------  Market action since Sydney’s end of day:  EQUITIES  New York: U.S. stocks climbed, building on last week’s rally,
amid growing speculation that the Federal Reserve will pump more
cash into the economy to protect the recovery.
*The S&P 500 rose 0.2 percent to 1,167.65 at 2:42 p.m. in New
York after advancing 1.7 percent last week.
*The Dow Jones Industrial Average increased 15.02 points, or 0.1
percent, to 11,021.50.
*JPMorgan Chase & Co., Boeing Co. and Alcoa Inc. led gains
in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.  London: European stocks climbed, extending the biggest weekly
gain in a month for the benchmark Stoxx Europe 600 Index, amid
continuing speculation that the Federal Reserve will step in to
support the economy.
*The Stoxx 600 gained 0.4 percent to 263.2 at the 4:30 p.m.
close in London as two stocks advanced for each one that
declined.
*The FTSE 100 rose 0.3 percent to 5,672.4 at the 4:30 p.m. close
in London, paring two days of losses.  Hong Kong: Asian stocks rose, with material and energy companies
leading a regional gauge to a two-year high, on speculation the
U.S. will join Japan and Australia in acting to shore up a
fragile global economic recovery.
*The MSCI Asia Pacific excluding Japan Index gained 0.5 percent
to 460.98 at 6:22 p.m. in Hong Kong.
*Hong Kong’s Hang Seng Index advanced 1.2 percent, while the
Shanghai Composite Index jumped 2.5 percent.  Sydney/Wellington: Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index rose 0.3
percent to 4,697.50 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in Sydney.
New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index increased 0.1 percent to 3,234.89 at
the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  FOREIGN EXCHANGE  New York: The dollar was near a 15-year low against the yen on
speculation the Federal Reserve will debase the currency by
signaling increased quantitative easing to reduce unemployment.
*The dollar was at 82.06 yen at 2:58 p.m. in New York, compared
with 81.93 yen on Oct. 8, after earlier reaching 81.39 yen, the
lowest level since April 1995.
*The U.S. currency advanced 0.4 percent to $1.3890 per euro,
from $1.3939.  COMMODITIES  New York: Gold futures rose to a record closing price on bets
that the dollar will resume a slump, boosting demand for
precious metals as an alternative investment. Silver extended a
rally to the highest level since 1980.
*Gold futures for December delivery rose $9.10, or 0.7 percent,
to settle at $1,354.40 an ounce at 1:37 p.m. on the Comex in New
York.  METALS  New York: Copper prices rose to a 27-month high in New York on
bets that the Federal Reserve will act to sustain the economic
recovery and boost demand for commodities.
*Copper futures for delivery in December rose 1.5 cents, or 0.4
percent, to close at $3.7895 a pound at 1:24 p.m. on the Comex
in New York.  OIL  New York: Crude oil dropped, snapping a three-week rally that
took prices to the highest levels since May, as the dollar
strengthened against the euro and the yen, curbing the appeal of
commodities as an alternative investment.
*Crude for November delivery lost 41 cents, or 0.4 percent, to
$82.25 a barrel at the 2:30 p.m. close of floor trading on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*National Australia Bank’s monthly business survey for September,
11:30 a.m. in Sydney.
*Climate Change Minister  Greg Combet  speaks at CarbonExpo
Australasia 2010.
*Day 1 of AB+F Corporate and Business Banking Forum.
*Victorian Premier  John Brumby  scheduled to address Australia-
Israel Chamber of Commerce luncheon in Melbourne.  ANALYST RATINGS: Upgrades, downgrades, new coverage
*AMP NZ Office Trust downgraded to “neutral” from “buy” at
UBS.  BLOOMBERG TV: Selected guests (Sydney time)
